{"id": "50788753cd4c47de878b5a9aef4fbb99", "timestamp": "2025-12-11 02:20:33", "name": "Scientist0", "content": "Selected Action: Action 1.  \nReasoning: Based on the rich and focused discussion so far, our team has already converged on a coherent, high-impact research direction: constructing a TableQA benchmark that systematically evaluates robustness through human-annotated adversarial perturbations across table headers, content, and questions. Key design principles are well-articulated—such as the use of contrastive test pairs, a fine-grained perturbation taxonomy grounded in real user behaviors, human-in-the-loop elicitation with intentional adversarial goals, and diagnostic metrics beyond accuracy. We have also identified scalable pathways via active adversarial elicitation and potential integration of LLM-generated candidates for human refinement. While further discussion could incrementally improve aspects of the design, the core vision is both technically sound and novel, addressing a clear gap in current TableQA evaluation practices. Confirming this topic now enables us to move forward with prototype development, annotation protocol design, and pilot testing—critical next steps that will themselves inform and refine the framework. Therefore, I believe we are ready to select this as our research topic and begin operationalizing it.", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[90mScientist0\u001b[0m"}
